data.label:
Most of the people with attrition have the following similarities:
1. From **Research & Development** department, followed by **Sales** and lastly Human Resources 
2. Have an Education level of 3 (**Bachelor**)
3. Graduated from **Life Sciences**
4. Are currently working as **Lab Technicians** / **Research Scientist** / **Sales Representative**
5. Have a **Job Satisfaction of 3**, followed by **1 (least satisfied)**

Notes:

It seems that it is least likely for research directors and managers to have attrition, 

probably because they are receiving the highest monthly income and highest job level possible. 

A possible reason for managers/research directors with attrition may be retirement as most of them are older than the other employees.

data.label:
Here we can observe that attrition is the most important variable, its importance value factor is even significantly higher than all the other variables. 

As we have found from the previous tree, overtime and attrition have a strong correlation with one another. 

From the correlation plot earlier, the **correlation** with overtime is **positive**. 

Employees **with attrition** are more likely those that **do not have overtime**. 

Possible reasons for this interesting finding may be that some employees want to work overtime to earn more but they don't see much of a difference in monthly income if they do. Or they want to work overtime but are not given the opportunity to as there are only limited allowance. Hence, employees may leave the company to look for other companies which allows them to work overtime and can earn much more by doing so.

##### Job Level
is the classification of authority and/or salary levels of positions in an organization. 

Ex. senior executives, executive, middle management, advisors, associate 


Each job role has different job levels. 

Ex. Senior Executive Manager or Executive Manager 


Different job levels have different monthly income.

The higher your job level, the higher your monthly income. 


From the bar charts we can also see 4 hierarchy: 

Highest- Managers and Research Directors 

2nd- Sales Executive, Manufacturing Director, Healthcare Representative

3rd- Research Scientist, Lab Technician, Human Resources

data.label:
There seems to be more **younger people with attrition**. 

This means that retirement is not the main reason for attrition. 

Then what may be other possible reasons for attrition?



According to a blog posted by Mahidhar Reddy,
Source: https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/top-5-reasons-employee-attrition-how-deal-mahidhar-reddy 

the top factors for attrition are listed below:

1. Money (other companies may be willing to pay more)
2. Quality of Work (mismatches between employees' capabilities and actual work)
3. Performance Pressure (pressured by high performing co-workers and demanding manager)
4. Friends (friend group may influence job change)
5. Location (company may be too far)




We shall look into variables related to these factors.

data.label:
From this barplot, we observe that those with attrition are receiving a lower monthly income than those without attrition. 

In addition, among employees without attrition, those from human resources department are earning more than sales and research. However among those with attrition, monthly income for human resources is the lowest. 



With just barplots and boxplots alone, our prediction may not be accurate because the height or size of the plots may be affected by the number of employees corresponding to that category (ex. there are very few employees without attrition, hence there may be bias in the boxplots) 

Therefore we decided to create a random forest for a better classification accuracy of people with and without attrition. 

The first step is to encode the numerical variables and then balancing.
### OneHotEncoding
